{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 15:39:44.512574", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission successful.\n\nSummary of submitted solution:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"SDN controller (20.0.0.100)\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"sdn_controller_crash\"]\n\nRecommended next remediation steps (not submitted, optional):\n1. Verify controller VM/process at 20.0.0.100 is running; restart the SDN controller service if crashed.\n2. If controller cannot be recovered quickly, set fail_mode to \"secure\" -> \"standalone\" (fail-mode \"secure\" vs \"standalone\"/fail-open varies by OVS version) or configure temporary local flows to allow host-to-host traffic. Specifically:\n   - ovs-vsctl set-fail-mode BRIDGE standalone\n   - Or restart ovs-vswitchd with a configuration that allows forwarding without controller.\n3. After controller restoration, confirm OVS bridges connect to controller (ovs-vsctl show), ovs-system and bridge internal interfaces are UP (ip link), and hosts can ARP and ping.\n4. Consider making the controller highly available (HA clustering or multiple controller entries in OVS configuration) to prevent single-point-of-failure.\n\nIf you want, I can prepare exact commands for controller checks and temporary OVS fail-open commands for the versions in use.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2313, "output_tokens": 264, "total_tokens": 2577, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
